article.description:
Antawn Jamison scored 32 points and Jason Richardson added 25 as the Golden State Warriors won their third
straight road game with a 118-114 overtime victory over the Toronto Raptors on Friday night.
article.headline: Jamison's 32 lead Warriors to third straight road win
article.linkText: Jamison outplays Carter to lift Warriors in Toronto
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- The Golden State Warriors have an opportunity to go 4-0 on a road trip for only the second time since moving to the Bay Area 41 years ago.
 
Jamison
Antawn Jamison scored 32 points and Jason Richardson added 25 as the Warriors won their third straight road game with a 118-114 overtime victory over the Toronto Raptors on Friday night. The Warriors, who end their trip in Minnesota on Sunday, led by three with 8.6 seconds left in regulation. But Gilbert Arenas fouled Toronto's Voshon Lenard as Lenard attempted an off-balance 3-pointer. Lenard then made all three of his free throws to tie it with 2.5 seconds left. "I probably would have been breaking everything in here if we had lost the game because of a call like that,'' Arenas said. "But we pulled it out and now we are 3-0.'' Arenas had six of his 15 points in overtime, including four free throws in the final 20 seconds to seal the victory. Earl Boykins had 13 of his 19 points in the fourth quarter for the Warriors, who also beat Atlanta and New York on their trip. The Warriors last went 4-0 on a four-game trip in 1969. "Whenever you go on the road you are usually happy with a .500 record. We have a chance to go 4-0,'' Boykins said. Jamison said the team has come a long way this past month. "To get three in a row on the road is very difficult,'' Jamison said. "We're just getting a certain kind of confidence. It doesn't matter who we are playing against, we feel we can compete against a lot of teams. I wouldn't even say we had this confidence a month ago. It's scary how things are really coming into place. We only care about winning.'' Lenard went 9-for-9 from the line and finished with 26 points for the Raptors, who had their four-game winning streak snapped. Boykins made two free throws to give Golden State a 100-93 lead with 18.8 seconds remaining in regulation. Toronto's Morris Peterson followed with a 3-pointer, but Richardson made one of two free throws with 14.5 seconds left. Peterson followed with another open 3-pointer, cutting the lead to two with 9.3 seconds remaining. Richardson then made his first free throw attempt before missing the second. Arenas then fouled Lenard as Lenard attempted his 3-pointer with 2.5 seconds left. Jamison made two straight offensive rebounds and tip-ins, giving Golden State a 109-108 lead in overtime. "I had to do something in overtime after letting Peterson make those 3-pointers,'' Jamison said. After Toronto's Jerome Williams committed a turnover, Arenas made two free throws with 41 seconds left. Adonal Foyle, Richardson and Bob Sura then each made one of two free throws before Arenas made four more in the final 20 seconds. "I thought we expended a lot of energy trying to get back into the game,'' Lenard said. "You have to take your hat off to a young team like that. I thought they played like veterans, especially in overtime.'' Jamison had 16 points and Richardson had 13 as Golden State led 55-48 at halftime. Richardson had seven points during a 13-0 run in the second quarter as the Warriors took a 13-point lead. Lenard's jumper, free throw and layup cut it to seven by halftime.

Game notes
The Warriors won in Toronto for the first time since Dec. 10, 1996. ... The Raptors have lost a league-high 335 man-games to injury compared to 58 for the Warriors, the second fewest in the league. ... Carter went 9-for-21 from the field for 20 points. ... Foyle had 13 rebounds.
